@phdthesis{Milner2018,
abstract = {"Robbing Peter to Pay Paul: Business, Government, and Wage-Price Policy, 1945-1980," explores efforts to solve one of the most vexing problems of 20 th century American political economy: how to achieve full employment without inflation. According to the conventional chronology of American political economy, the stimulus of World War II encouraged postwar policymakers to employ Keynesian fiscal and monetary policies in the place of the microeconomic regulations and reforms utilized during the Progressive Era and New Deal. Recent scholarship has recast this interpretation by linking the embrace of macroeconomic stabilization to the efforts of conservative business groups to dismantle the legacy of the New Deal, especially its support for organized labor. This dissertation challenges these narratives by demonstrating how a prewar policy of raising labor's purchasing power in order to combat depression transformed into a postwar Keynesian solution for inflation known as wage-price policy, which called for restraining wages in order to stabilize costs and prices.   During the Progressive Era, economists theorized that firms and unions could exploit their market power to siphon off income for themselves, behavior popularly known as "robbing Peter to pay Paul." Fearing that this scramble for income would result in insufficient purchasing power to sustain employment, economists proposed to boost demand at its source through a wage-price policy under which wages rose at the same rate as did national labor productivity. The postwar "Keynesian Consensus" rendered this use of wage-price policy obsolete by demonstrating that the government could maintain demand directly through fiscal and monetary stimulus, but it also described how the market power of firms and unions could take advantage of these macroeconomic policies to create a "cost-push" inflation. The Consensus concluded that wages must now be held to the limit of productivity so that the government could pursue full employment without having to tolerate cost-push inflation.   Importantly, this dissertation argues that wage-price policy initially developed as the business community sought to adapt the New Deal order to the postwar economic climate. Historians working in the records of unions and business associations have recently interpreted developments in labor relations during this period as evidence of a conservative counter-offensive against the New Deal. This dissertation challenges this analysis of postwar corporate conservatism through case studies of three leading industries: motor vehicles, electrical equipment, and steel. By drawing upon never before cited corporate records from firms including Ford Motors, General Motors, General Electric, and U.S. Steel, this dissertation exposes how the leading firms of the core industrial economy collaborated with economists and one another in order to repurpose the adversarial system of labor relations envisioned by the New Deal into the basis of a non-inflationary wage-price policy. By reconstructing collective bargaining negotiations around new measures of productivity, firms hoped to contain their labor costs and so meet their financial and competitive objectives without having to wage an uphill political battle against organized labor.   At first, the federal government looked favorably on voluntary private efforts to combat cost-push inflation, limiting its direct interventions outside of wartime to generalized exhortations for restraint and private statesmanship. By the late 1950s, however, the Keynesian Consensus had concluded that the government would inevitably face a tradeoff between inflation and unemployment until it exercised direct control over costs. Over the course of the 1960s and 1970s, policymakers at the White House, Congress, and even the Federal Reserve transfored the previously voluntary wage-price policy into the basis for federal incomes policies so that the specter of inflation would not distract the government from the pursuit of full employment. For a brief period in the early 1970s, these federal efforts also enjoyed the support of the business sector, which had become convinced that its voluntary efforts at wage-price restraint were no longer effective in the face of a hostile labor climate. With time, however, this reliance on microeconomic control undercut the macroeconomic promises of the Keynesian Consensus as it failed to provide a solution to the misery of stagflation. Only in the 1980s, when the industrial-labor order that had given rise to wage-price policy in the early 20th collapsed, would policymakers recognize that they could fulfill the objectives of the Keynesian Consensus without being held hostage to big business and big labor.},
