@phdthesis{Clark2017,
abstract = {These essays consider why a benevolent monetary authority faced with an exploitable asset price channel might implement overly loose monetary policy, and they explore potential unintended consequences arising from a persistent regime of low real interest rates and high asset prices. In the first essay, I propose a general equilibrium model of monetary policy in which the monetary authority faces an exploitable asset price channel but also a time consistency problem. The model predicts that the monetary authority implements sub-optimally loose policy, leading to a socially excessive degree of financial instability, consistent with recent critiques of the Federal Reserve's unconventional policies since 2009.    The second essay slightly revises the model to investigate how exogenous variation in the risk-free real interest rate and asset prices influences capital accumulation, private sector indebtedness, the size of the financial sector, bank system loan losses, and the evolution of wealth inequality across households. I argue that high asset prices induced by a persistent policy regime of very low real interest rates give rise to growing private sector indebtedness, a larger “high finance” sector, a higher loan loss ratio in the banking system, and greater wealth disparities. I argue, further, that the effect of variation in asset prices on capital investment, while generally positive, attenuates at high asset valuation levels, and that higher asset prices can become counter-productive in stimulating investment when asset market valuations are sufficiently high. The third essay presents a variety of evidence from advanced economies between 1960 and 2015, with results generally consistent with the theoretical predictions of the second essay.},
