@phdthesis{Goodliffe2008,
abstract = {This dissertation attempts to account for the resurgence of the Far Right in France since the establishment of democracy in the country in the final quarter of the nineteenth Century. Taking to task historical treatments of this political phenomenon for their failure to specify the conditions and dynamics attending its emergence, and faulting the historical myopia of contemporary institutionalist accounts, the dissertation explains the continuing appeal of the Far Right by relating the socio-structural outcomes of French industrialization and democratization to the persistence of an illiberal political culture within French society. Specifically, it argues that, as a result of France's protracted and uneven experience of industrialization and urbanization, significant ‘pre-' or ‘anti-modern' social classes subsisted late into the country's development which remained functionally ill-adapted and culturally ill-disposed to liberal capitalism and democracy. Historically incorporating what have been termed the ‘traditional middle classes' and, more recently, a growing stratum of the working class, these groups progressively turned against the process of capitalist modernization as well as the Republican state that oversaw it. The study concludes that these groups developed an illiberal political worldview or ‘culture' which made them receptive to the authoritarian and xenophobic prescriptions of the Far Right in periods of economic and social crisis.    This study employs a multi-disciplinary approach. At a first level, it draws on the principles of historical sociology in order to situate movements of the French Far Right in their broader social, economic and political contexts, and to specify the cultural dispositions of the social groups who supported them. Second, the dissertation also studies interest group aggregation as well as institutional and electoral processes in order to understand the political dynamics attending the emergence of these movement