@phdthesis{Kershaw2014,
abstract = {"Arrested Development" investigates a series of monetary crises in the US and Mexico in the late 1960s and 1970s to explain how and why government officials in both countries abandoned postwar growth projects in favor of neoliberal development projects, despite the slower growth, lower real wages, rising social instabilities and more frequent market failures that emerged as a result. The project demonstrates that US and Mexican officials formulated and implemented domestic and foreign policies based on their perceptions of the political and economic costs and benefits of the various policy programs they considered, rather than on a growing faith in neoliberal ideas, as other scholars have suggested. US and Mexican authorities, even those in the administrations of Ronald Reagan and Miguel de la Madrid, both fervent supporters of free market ideas, were quick to formulate policy that ran contrary to their principles when indulging their beliefs threatened to place them at a political disadvantage. Instead, neoliberal ideas rose to prominence in the 1970s because they became politically useful, performing an essential ideological function that legitimated the development projects and the state authorities who implemented them, even when the policy initiatives diverged from neoliberal principles. Through its focus on the pragmatic politics of growth and development, this dissertation explains the origins of the neoliberal development projects that proliferated around the world in the late twentieth century, providing a new periodization of neoliberalism and a historical and analytical specificity to a widely used but poorly historicized term.},
